the cost in making the code harder to parse (both for compilers and, IMO, humans) isn&#x27;t worth it.  Using short assignment mixed with if makes the Go error handling branch code not so bad, eg instead of:<p><pre><code>  err = doSomething

  if err != nil {
    return err
  }
</code></pre>
do:<p><pre><code>  if err = doSomething(); err != nil {
    return err
  }
</code></pre>
Also if your function only returns err, I&#x27;d use a named return to save even more typing.  I know they are seen as a bit of a red-headed stepchild by much of the Go community these days, but I still like them if used carefully:<p><pre><code>  func whatever() (err error) {
    if err = doSomething(); err != nil {
       return
    }

    ...

  }</code></pre>
